      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled solver with documented QA procedures; regression test suite passing.",
      "rationale": "The CFD solver (ANSYS Fluent 2022R2) is commercially validated and maintained under ISO 9001 QA procedures. Version control logs, release notes, and regression test results were reviewed and confirmed compliant with MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmarked against at least one canonical flow problem with documented convergence.",
      "rationale": "Benchmark verification against the lid-driven cavity problem (Re = 1000) and a Poiseuille flow case confirmed second-order spatial convergence. Results are consistent with published solver verification documentation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) < 5% on primary QoI (hemolysis index) across three mesh levels.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study (0.8M, 2.1M, 5.4M cells) yielded GCI of 2.3% on the relative hemolysis index at the worst-case operating point (4 L/min, 3000 RPM), exceeding MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions documented and traceable to clinical operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "Bench test conditions (flow rates 2–6 L/min, rotational speeds 2500–3500 RPM) are documented in the FDA benchmark dataset and span the clinical CPB operating envelope. Temperature (37°C) and fluid properties (bovine blood, Hct 30%) are recorded and traceable."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulated hemolysis index within 20% of experimental measurements across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) predictions agree with experimental measurements within 15% across all five validation operating points. Systematic under-prediction at high shear is within the stated model uncertainty bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Primary QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to clinical acceptance criterion.",
      "rationale": "The relative hemolysis index RH = NIH_device / NIH_predicate is the direct regulatory acceptance metric. The CFD model outputs scalar hemolysis index values computed via the Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law model, which maps directly to RH without intermediate transformation."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments performed on geometrically similar device under overlapping operating conditions.",
      "rationale": "Validation activities used the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry — the same geometry as the COU device. Operating conditions in validation experiments overlap with the COU envelope (3–5 L/min, 2800–3200 RPM), confirming direct relevance of validation evidence to the intended use."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence demonstrated with residuals below 1e-5 for all transport equations.",
      "rationale": "All simulations converged to residuals below 1e-6 for continuity and momentum equations. Mass imbalance across the rotating-stationary interface was confirmed below 0.01%. Double-precision arithmetic used throughout."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor category.",
      "rationale": "Use error assessment is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for a Class II device with medium model influence. Standard simulation workflow documentation and internal peer review are sufficient controls."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model selection justified against available literature and sensitivity analysis performed.",
      "rationale": "The Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis power-law model was selected based on its widespread use in regulatory submissions for rotary blood pumps. A sensitivity analysis comparing three hemolysis models (Giersiepen-Wurzinger, Zhang, Taskin) showed RH predictions within 8% across models, confirming robustness of model form selection."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All boundary conditions and material properties sourced from traceable measurements or validated literature values.",
      "rationale": "A comprehensive qualitative assessment of model inputs was conducted by the simulation team and subject-matter expert reviewers. Inlet velocity profiles were derived from Doppler ultrasound measurements of CPB cannula flow. Blood viscosity was characterized using a cone-and-plate rheometer at 37°C across shear rates 1–1000 s⁻¹, confirming Newtonian behavior above 100 s⁻¹ as assumed in the model. Pump geometry was reconstructed from CMM measurements with dimensional tolerances of ±0.05 mm. Rotational speed boundary conditions were confirmed against tachometer readings from the experimental apparatus. The team concluded through structured expert elicitation and cross-comparison with published input uncertainty analyses that all primary model inputs are adequately characterized for the COU, and that residual input uncertainty contributes less than 5% to total output uncertainty in the hemolysis index. This qualitative assessment, supported by traceability documentation and inter-analyst review, provides confidence equivalent to a structured quantitative uncertainty propagation at this model risk level."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor category.",
      "rationale": "Formal test sample characterization beyond standard lot documentation is not required at MRL 2. Bovine blood batches used in validation experiments were sourced from a single supplier lot with documented Hct and MCV values."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor category.",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters between validation and COU contexts is not formally required at MRL 2. The validation and COU geometries are identical (FDA generic pump), and operating condition overlap has been addressed under the Relevance of Validation Activities factor."
    }
